{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U2bSanbiDjm6Ws9p2DG3oF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5→container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6→results to a git branch.\n     7→\n     8→## Core Concepts\n     9→\n    10→- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11→- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12→- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13→- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14→- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15→\n    16→## Workflow DSL\n    17→\n    18→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19→declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20→no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21→\n    22→### Minimal Example\n    23→\n    24→```\n    25→workflow \"develop\" {\n    26→  step implement {\n    27→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28→    results = [success, fail]\n    29→  }\n    30→\n    31→  step test {\n    32→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33→    results = [success, fail]\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  implement:success -> test\n    37→  implement:fail -> abort\n    38→  test:success -> done\n    39→  test:fail -> abort\n    40→}\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→### Step Configuration\n    44→\n    45→| Key | Type | Description |\n    46→|-----|------|-------------|\n    47→| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48→| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49→| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50→| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51→| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52→| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53→| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54→| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55→| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56→| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57→\n    58→A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59→\n    60→### The `file()` Function\n    61→\n    62→`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63→(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64→templates:\n    65→\n    66→```\n    67→prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→### The `container {}` Block\n    71→\n    72→Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73→\n    74→**Step level** — per-step container config:\n    75→```\n    76→step code {\n    77→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78→  container {\n    79→    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81→    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82→  }\n    83→  results = [success, fail]\n    84→}\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n    88→```\n    89→workflow \"develop\" {\n    90→  container {\n    91→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92→    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94→  }\n    95→  ...\n    96→}\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100→\n   101→### The `host {}` Block\n   102→\n   103→Can appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\n   104→with a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105→\n   106→```\n   107→workflow \"main\" {\n   108→  host {\n   109→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   110→  }\n   111→  ...\n   112→}\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   116→`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   117→\n   118→### Wiring Syntax\n   119→\n   120→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   121→\n   122→```\n   123→implement:success -> test\n   124→implement:fail -> abort\n   125→test:success -> done\n   126→test:fail -> fix\n   127→```\n   128→\n   129→### Wire Output Mappings\n   130→\n   131→Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→Path expressions:\n   138→\n   139→| Expression | Meaning |\n   140→|---|---|\n   141→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   142→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   143→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   144→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   145→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   146→\n   147→If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   148→text, only bare `output` works.\n   149→\n   150→### Retry Loops\n   151→\n   152→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   153→\n   154→```\n   155→test:fail -> fix\n   156→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   157→fix:fail -> abort\n   158→```\n   159→\n   160→Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   161→\n   162→```\n   163→step fix {\n   164→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   165→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   166→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   167→}\n   168→```\n   169→\n   170→### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   171→\n   172→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   173→\n   174→```\n   175→test:success -> lint\n   176→test:success -> quality\n   177→```\n   178→\n   179→### Collect (Join)\n   180→\n   181→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   182→\n   183→```\n   184→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   185→collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   189→\n   190→### Comments\n   191→\n   192→Line comments with `//`:\n   193→\n   194→```\n   195→// This is a comment\n   196→implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   197→```\n   198→\n   199→## Result Protocol\n   200→\n   201→Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   202→\n   203→```\n   204→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   205→```\n   206→\n   207→For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   208→\n   209→Rules:\n   210→- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   211→- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   212→- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   213→- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   214→- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   215→\n   216→## Prompt Assembly\n   217→\n   218→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   219→\n   220→1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   221→2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   222→3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   223→4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   224→\n   225→The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   226→\n   227→## Agent Command Resolution\n   228→\n   229→Priority (highest to lowest):\n   230→1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   231→2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   232→3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   233→4. Default: `claude`\n   234→\n   235→### Fallback Chains\n   236→\n   237→Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   238→\n   239→```\n   240→agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   241→```\n   242→\n   243→- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n   244→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n   245→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   246→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   247→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   248→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   249→\n   250→Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   251→\n   252→### Agent Setup Guides\n   253→\n   254→For detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   255→\n   256→- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — session-based auth, no API key needed\n   257→- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — API key configuration\n   258→\n   259→## Workflow Locations\n   260→\n   261→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   262→via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   263→\n   264→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   265→Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267→execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268→fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269→\n   270→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272→\n   273→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274→|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278→\n   279→Additionally, `host.cloche` may define a **`release-task`** utility workflow. This is\n   280→not part of the automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\n   281→web dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. A task is\n   282→considered stale when it has `in_progress` status but no active worker is running for\n   283→it (e.g. after a failed run or daemon restart). The workflow receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`.\n   284→\n   285→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   286→mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   287→\n   288→### list-tasks Output Format\n   289→\n   290→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   291→object:\n   292→\n   293→| Field | Required | Description |\n   294→|-------|----------|-------------|\n   295→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   296→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   297→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   298→| `description` | no | Full description |\n   299→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   300→\n   301→The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   302→set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   303→deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   304→\n   305→### Host Workflow Example\n   306→\n   307→A three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   308→\n   309→```\n   310→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   311→  step fetch-tickets {\n   312→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   313→    results = [success, fail]\n   314→  }\n   315→\n   316→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   317→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   318→}\n   319→\n   320→workflow \"main\" {\n   321→  host {\n   322→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   323→  }\n   324→\n   325→  step prepare-prompt {\n   326→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   327→    results = [success, fail]\n   328→  }\n   329→\n   330→  step develop {\n   331→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   332→    results       = [success, fail]\n   333→  }\n   334→\n   335→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   336→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   337→  develop:success        -> done\n   338→  develop:fail           -> done\n   339→}\n   340→\n   341→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   342→  step push-for-review {\n   343→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   344→    results = [success, fail]\n   345→  }\n   346→\n   347→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   348→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   349→}\n   350→```\n   351→\n   352→The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   353→receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   354→workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   355→what cleanup to perform.\n   356→\n   357→### Host Step Environment Variables\n   358→\n   359→| Variable | Description |\n   360→|----------|-------------|\n   361→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   362→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   363→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   364→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   365→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   366→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   367→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   368→| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   369→\n   370→### Container Environment Variables\n   371→\n   372→| Variable | Description |\n   373→|----------|-------------|\n   374→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   375→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   376→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   377→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   378→\n   379→## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   380→\n   381→The `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\n   382→When you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\n   383→generated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\n   384→to automate task discovery and cleanup.\n   385→\n   386→The daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n   387→\n   388→1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n   389→2. **`main`** — execute the work\n   390→3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n   391→\n   392→A fourth optional workflow, **`release-task`**, can be defined for releasing stale\n   393→claimed tasks back to open status. It is not part of the automatic loop — it runs on\n   394→demand when triggered from the web dashboard's Release button.\n   395→\n   396→All these workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\n   397→required; `list-tasks`, `finalize`, and `release-task` are optional.\n   398→\n   399→### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n   400→\n   401→The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   402→tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   403→\n   404→**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   405→loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   406→\n   407→**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   408→`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   409→\n   410→```json\n   411→{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   412→{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   413→{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   414→```\n   415→\n   416→The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   417→Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   418→5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   419→\n   420→**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   421→\n   422→```\n   423→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   424→  step fetch-tickets {\n   425→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   426→    results = [success, fail]\n   427→  }\n   428→\n   429→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   430→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   431→}\n   432→```\n   433→\n   434→**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\n   435→once without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\n   436→runs manually with `cloche run`.\n   437→\n   438→### `main` — Executing Work\n   439→\n   440→The `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n   441→`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n   442→\n   443→**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\n   444→is absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\n   445→selected task.\n   446→\n   447→**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\n   448→then dispatches a container workflow:\n   449→\n   450→```\n   451→workflow \"main\" {\n   452→  host {\n   453→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   454→  }\n   455→\n   456→  step prepare-prompt {\n   457→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   458→    results = [success, fail]\n   459→  }\n   460→\n   461→  step develop {\n   462→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   463→    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   464→    results       = [success, fail]\n   465→  }\n   466→\n   467→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   468→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   469→  develop:success        -> done\n   470→  develop:fail           -> done\n   471→}\n   472→```\n   473→\n   474→The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\n   475→it completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\n   476→used as the prompt for the container run.\n   477→\n   478→You can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n   479→`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n   480→`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n   481→\n   482→### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n   483→\n   484→The `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\n   485→of whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n   486→\n   487→**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\n   488→sets two additional environment variables:\n   489→\n   490→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n   491→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n   492→\n   493→**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n   494→\n   495→```\n   496→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   497→  step close-task {\n   498→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n   499→    results = [success, fail]\n   500→  }\n   501→\n   502→  close-task:success -> done\n   503→  close-task:fail    -> done\n   504→}\n   505→```\n   506→\n   507→A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\n   508→closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   509→Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the finalize workflow itself\n   510→completes rather than aborting. Note that the overall task status reflects the\n   511→worst outcome of the main and finalize phases — if finalize fails, the task is\n   512→marked as failed even when main succeeded.\n   513→\n   514→**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   515→don't need automated cleanup.\n   516→\n   517→### `release-task` — Releasing Stale Claims\n   518→\n   519→The `release-task` workflow handles releasing tasks that are stuck in `in_progress`\n   520→status without an active worker. This happens when a run fails, the daemon restarts,\n   521→or a container is lost. The web dashboard detects these stale tasks and shows a\n   522→**Release** button next to them.\n   523→\n   524→**When it runs:** On demand, when a user clicks Release in the web dashboard. The\n   525→daemon sets `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` to the task being released.\n   526→\n   527→**How to configure:**\n   528→\n   529→```\n   530→workflow \"release-task\" {\n   531→  step release-task {\n   532→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/release-task.sh\"\n   533→    results = [success, fail]\n   534→  }\n   535→\n   536→  release-task:success -> done\n   537→  release-task:fail    -> abort\n   538→}\n   539→```\n   540→\n   541→A typical release script returns the ticket to `open` status and unassigns the owner\n   542→in your task tracker.\n   543→\n   544→**If omitted:** The Release button will not function. Stale tasks must be manually\n   545→unclaimed in your task tracker.\n   546→\n   547→### Putting It All Together\n   548→\n   549→The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   550→\n   551→1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   552→2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   553→3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   554→4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   555→5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   556→\n   557→Start the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n   558→`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n   559→\n   560→## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   561→\n   562→```\n   563→workflow \"develop\" {\n   564→  step implement {\n   565→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   566→    results = [success, fail]\n   567→  }\n   568→\n   569→  step test {\n   570→    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   571→    results = [success, fail]\n   572→  }\n   573→\n   574→  step lint {\n   575→    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   576→    results = [success, fail]\n   577→  }\n   578→\n   579→  step quality {\n   580→    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   581→    results = [success, fail]\n   582→  }\n   583→\n   584→  step fix {\n   585→    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   586→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   587→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   588→  }\n   589→\n   590→  implement:success -> test\n   591→  implement:fail -> abort\n   592→\n   593→  test:success -> lint\n   594→  test:success -> quality\n   595→  test:fail -> fix\n   596→\n   597→  lint:fail -> fix\n   598→  quality:fail -> fix\n   599→  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   600→\n   601→  fix:success -> test\n   602→  fix:fail -> abort\n   603→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   604→}\n   605→```\n   606→\n   607→## Container Isolation Model\n   608→\n   609→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   610→- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   611→- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   612→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   613→- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   614→\n   615→Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   616→\n   617→## CLI Reference\n   618→\n   619→Every subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\n   620→examples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n   621→\n   622→```\n   623→cloche --help              # top-level overview\n   624→cloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\n   625→cloche run --help          # same as above\n   626→```\n   627→\n   628→### `cloche init`\n   629→\n   630→Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   631→\n   632→```\n   633→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   634→```\n   635→\n   636→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   637→|------|---------|-------------|\n   638→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   639→| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   640→\n   641→Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   642→host workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   643→\n   644→### `cloche run`\n   645→\n   646→Launch a workflow run.\n   647→\n   648→```\n   649→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   650→```\n   651→\n   652→| Flag | Description |\n   653→|------|-------------|\n   654→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   655→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   656→| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   657→| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   658→\n   659→Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   660→when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   661→\n   662→### `cloche status`\n   663→\n   664→```\n   665→cloche status <run-id>\n   666→```\n   667→\n   668→Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   669→\n   670→### `cloche list`\n   671→\n   672→```\n   673→cloche list [flags]\n   674→```\n   675→\n   676→Lists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   677→Results can be filtered by state, project, issue, or limited to a fixed number.\n   678→\n   679→| Flag | Description |\n   680→|------|-------------|\n   681→| `--all` | Show runs from all projects (default: current project only). |\n   682→| `--project, -p DIR` | Filter by project directory. |\n   683→| `--state, -s STATE` | Filter by run state (`pending`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, `cancelled`). |\n   684→| `--limit, -n NUM` | Limit the number of results returned. |\n   685→| `--issue, -i ID` | Filter by issue/task ID. |\n   686→\n   687→### `cloche logs`\n   688→\n   689→```\n   690→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n   691→```\n   692→\n   693→| Flag | Description |\n   694→|------|-------------|\n   695→| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   696→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   697→| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   698→\n   699→Without `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   700→\n   701→### `cloche poll`\n   702→\n   703→```\n   704→cloche poll <run-id> [run-id...]\n   705→```\n   706→\n   707→Block until all specified runs finish. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 if all runs succeeded, 1 if any failed or were cancelled.\n   708→\n   709→With a single run ID, prints step-level progress. With multiple run IDs, displays a compact status summary (e.g. `id1: running`) and re-prints whenever a state changes. Use `cloche logs` for detailed output of individual runs.\n   710→\n   711→### `cloche stop`\n   712→\n   713→```\n   714→cloche stop <run-id>\n   715→```\n   716→\n   717→### `cloche delete`\n   718→\n   719→```\n   720→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   721→```\n   722→\n   723→Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   724→\n   725→### `cloche health`\n   726→\n   727→```\n   728→cloche health\n   729→```\n   730→\n   731→Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   732→\n   733→### `cloche workflow`\n   734→\n   735→```\n   736→cloche workflow [--project <dir>]\n   737→cloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n   738→```\n   739→\n   740→List all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n   741→\n   742→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   743→|------|---------|-------------|\n   744→| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n   745→\n   746→With no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\n   747→workflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\n   748→Wires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\n   749→blue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\n   750→for readability.\n   751→\n   752→### `cloche project`\n   753→\n   754→Show project info and config.\n   755→\n   756→```\n   757→cloche project [--name <label>]\n   758→```\n   759→\n   760→By default, looks up the project by the current working directory. Use `--name` to look\n   761→up a project by its registered label instead.\n   762→\n   763→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   764→|------|---------|-------------|\n   765→| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n   766→\n   767→Output includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, evolution),\n   768→orchestrator loop state (running/stopped), currently active runs, and known container\n   769→and host workflow names.\n   770→\n   771→### `cloche get`\n   772→\n   773→```\n   774→cloche get <key>\n   775→```\n   776→\n   777→Get a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   778→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   779→the current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   780→\n   781→### `cloche set`\n   782→\n   783→```\n   784→cloche set <key> <value|->\n   785→```\n   786→\n   787→Set a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   788→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   789→the current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   790→Pass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   791→\n   792→### `cloche tasks`\n   793→\n   794→```\n   795→cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   796→```\n   797→\n   798→Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   799→upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   800→state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   801→\n   802→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   803→|------|---------|-------------|\n   804→| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   805→\n   806→### `cloche loop`\n   807→\n   808→Start or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n   809→tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n   810→\n   811→```\n   812→cloche loop [--max <n>]\n   813→cloche loop stop\n   814→```\n   815→\n   816→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   817→|------|---------|-------------|\n   818→| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n   819→\n   820→`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n   821→\n   822→### `cloche --version`\n   823→\n   824→Print version information for all Cloche components.\n   825→\n   826→```\n   827→cloche -v\n   828→cloche --version\n   829→```\n   830→\n   831→Displays the CLI version, queries the running daemon for its version (via gRPC),\n   832→and runs `docker run --rm --entrypoint cloche-agent <image> -v` to get the agent\n   833→version from the project's container image. If the daemon is unreachable or the\n   834→image doesn't exist, the corresponding version shows `<unavailable>`. Version\n   835→mismatches between components produce warnings on stderr.\n   836→\n   837→The daemon and agent binaries also support standalone version output:\n   838→\n   839→```\n   840→cloched -v       # prints daemon version\n   841→cloche-agent -v  # prints agent version\n   842→```\n   843→\n   844→### `cloche shutdown`\n   845→\n   846→```\n   847→cloche shutdown\n   848→```\n   849→\n   850→## Project Layout\n   851→\n   852→```\n   853→my-project/\n   854→├── .cloche/\n   855→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   856→│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   857→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   858→│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n   859→│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   860→│   │   ├── implement.md\n   861→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   862→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   863→│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   864→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   865→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   866→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   867→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   868→│       ├── context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   869→│       ├── output/\n   870→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n   871→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   872→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   873→│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   874→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   875→├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   876→└── .git/\n   877→```\n   878→\n   879→## Daemon Configuration\n   880→\n   881→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   882→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   883→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   884→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   885→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   886→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   887→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   888→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   889→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   890→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   891→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   892→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   893→\n   894→### Client Configuration\n   895→\n   896→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   897→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   898→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   899→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   900→\n   901→## Dockerfile Requirements\n   902→\n   903→The container image must have:\n   904→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   905→- `git` installed\n   906→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   907→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   908→- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   909→\n   910→## Build Commands\n   911→\n   912→```\n   913→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   914→make test           # Run all tests\n   915→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   916→make lint           # Run go vet\n   917→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   918→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   919→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   920→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   921→```\n   922→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01X39tUhxFjzAhiJaof3xvLs","session_id":"80e1ce2e-a764-409e-b43f-733763e5218d","uuid":"4790900d-5a09-470c-9311-8a4e0a91b771"}
